To remove the marker (bullet or numbering) from a list item, you can use CSS to style the elements. There are a few different approaches you can take depending on the type of list element you are using.

1. For an unordered list (`<ul>`) with bullets, you can use the `list-style` property to remove the bullet point:

```css
ul {
  list-style: none;
}
```

2. For an ordered list (`<ol>`) with numbering, you can use the `list-style-type` property with a value of "none" to remove the numbering:

```css
ol {
  list-style-type: none;
}
```

3. If you want to remove the marker for a specific list item within an unordered or ordered list, you can give that item a class and style it accordingly:

```css
<ul>
  <li class="no-marker">List item 1</li>
  <li>List item 2</li>
</ul>

.no-marker {
  list-style: none;
}
```

In the above examples, the CSS styles are targeting the `<ul>` or `<ol>` elements and removing the default marker. If you want to remove the marker for a specific list item, you can give it a class and target it in CSS like `.no-marker`.
